post_text:
Community Meeting - Learning Continuity and Attendance Plan

Students, families, staff and members of the community make NUSD the caring place it is, and we consider everyone’s input invaluable to our plans to provide the best possible learning experiences.

In response to the COVID-19 pandemic, California State Senate Bill 98 signed by Governor Newsom changes the parameters for operating schools and accountability requirements. Instead of a 2020-21 LCAP, school districts are required to complete a Learning Continuity and Attendance Plan (LCP) at the start of the 2020-21 school year. Like the LCAP, the California Department of Education (CDE) requires that school districts engage stakeholders when developing the LCP.

We respectfully invite the NUSD community to Facebook Live meeting on Monday, August 31, 2020.

• Simultaneous Spanish interpretation will be available during the meeting.
• Participants will be able to submit comments in writing in English and Spanish on Facebook.
• Student participation is encouraged.

post_text:
Culinary Class Going Strong During
Remote Learning at Marin Oaks High School

Chicken Tetrazzini, Shepard’s Pie, and Lasagna are a few of the recipes students in the Culinary Class at Marin Oaks High School have been cooking during this time of remote learning.

While they can’t cook together at school, students are cooking at home for their families. Each Thursday, Culinary Class teacher John Matern gathers the ingredients for the day’s recipe for students to pick up at 10 am. At 2 pm the same day, Mr. Matern holds a Zoom cooking class demonstrating the day’s recipe. After a few hours, the students send Mr. Matern photos of their finished product which is usually dinner for their family that evening.

The Culinary Class at Marin Oaks is one of the offerings under NUSD’s California Technical Education (CTE) program and is funded by a Perkins Grant. The class is also open to students at Novato and San Marin High Schools.

post_text:
With a generous donation from First Book and New York Life, and a matching grant from the The Book Place: Friends of the Marin County Free Library, the South Novato Library purchased almost 800 books, including bilingual titles. Volunteers from the library staff and FANS distributed the books last week at the Hill Education Center and Hamilton School during lunch.

As families drove up to pick up lunch, staff offered them a book. They then drove up to the "Book Bistro" and were given some quick "Reader's Advisory" and passed books through the car window.

Thank you!!

#nusdrocks

post_text:
Register new students NOW for NUSD!

NUSD is finalizing the number of classes for each grade level for the 2020-2021 school year.

Please register your new student by May 1, 2020, to ensure your child has a spot in your neighborhood school. If your child’s registration is in progress, please complete it ASAP. While all residents are guaranteed a spot in a Novato Unified school, it is possible your child will be assigned a school outside your neighborhood. The earlier your child is registered the more likely your child will attend your neighborhood school.
Here is the link for online registration – no need to visit the school at this time!

https://nusd.org/schoolmintaccount/

Congratulations Liz Feingold! Liz is a School Projects/Fiscal Specialist at Hamilton School K-8. She is recognized for her character as she goes above and beyond her job with a smile and is always willing to help out.

"Modeling the Way" is a NUSD employee recognition program for "modeling" at least one of the 6 C's in the Graduate Profile and one of the five NUSD values. Recipients are nominated by their co-workers, peers, parents or students.

More information, and the nomination form, can be found at the link below.

http://nusd.org/departments/human-resources-2/employee-appreciation/

Message from local doctors: “Local hospitals in Marin & SF are running low on personal protective equipment (masks, gloves, goggles, face shields), with some having less than a 2-week supply.

post_text:
During this time of suspended site-based learning, NUSD has established a Remote Learning Webpage with a library of resources for grades PK-12 that you can find here: https://nusd.org/remote-learning/
● Teachers in grades 3-12 will be updating Google Classrooms every day with new learning activities
● If your child needs a device or internet hotspot during the closure, please contact your school site’s main office.
● Teachers and Counselors will be responding to student emails during regular school hours.
● Students are expected to complete all assignments provided by teachers during this time.
● Assignments are meant to maintain continuity of learning, but does not replicate in-class experiences such as science labs, group discussions, etc.
● Keep checking our website https://nusd.org/remote-learning/ for the latest information and support for remote learning.
● If you do not have home access to the internet, please e-mail help@nusd.org or call 415-493-4299.

post_text: Measure G Update: One of our projects for Summer 2019 was the HVAC upgrade installation at Lynwood Elementary, Olive Elementary and Loma Verde Elementary. The new system replaces existing gas heating furnaces with energy efficient heat pumps connected to exterior condensing units. Supported by the District's existing Pelican climate control system, this project brings both heating and cooling capacity in each classroom at the three school sites. #nusdrocks #MeasureG #AGreatSchoolsForAGreaterNovato

post_text: Measure G Update: The District's Food and Nutritional Services (FANS) operation was moved off of the Lynwood Elementary campus, and relocated in a newly renovated distribution center at our Olive Avenue warehouse. Centralizing the program creates operational efficiencies while getting a District function off of a school site campus. Staff moved in and the new facility became operational in February 2020. #nusdrocks #MeasureG #GreatSchoolsForAGreaterNovato

A few questions have been going around about the beef at NUSD. Here’s what Cody Williams, Director of Food & Nutrition Services, has said,

“NUSD Food and Nutrition Department continues to purchase quality products through local farms such as Marin Sun Farms grass-fed meat raised by California ranchers and Mindful Meats, an organic, non-GMO project verified, pasture raised meat company by Marin & Sonoma County ranchers. Their Mindful Meats beef line has several products with an approved Child Nutrition Label and is currently distributed through our main distributor.” "...and all our chicken is antibiotic free."

http://www.marinsunfarms.com/ http://www.mindfulmeats.com/

UPDATE: The children were found safe. Thank you to all those who helped.

Please reach out to the Novato Police Department if you have any information about Jonathan and Madeline. They are in our thoughts.
shared_text:
Novato Police Department
November 28, 2019 at 6:02 PM ·

MISSING:

The Novato Police Department seeks your help in locating: Jonathan, age 13, and Madeline, age 11. No clothing description is available. Both children are missing from the area of Leafwood Dr, and were last seen at approximately 5:30pm on November 27th. Jonathan and Madeline left their residence following an argument with their parents and have not yet returned. Due to Jonathan and Madelines age, and cold weather conditions, officers diligently pursued leads and actively searched for the children throughout the night. There are no known suspicious circumstance associated with their disapperance. We are continuing our search and would appreciate the publics' assistance in locating both children.

If you have information that can assist in helping safely locate Jonathan or Madeline, please call 911 or (415) 897-1122.
text:
UPDATE: The children were found safe. Thank you to all those who helped.

Please reach out to the Novato Police Department if you have any information about Jonathan and Madeline. They are in our thoughts.

November 19, 2019, 2:30 pm - Based upon the best information currently available from PG&E, Novato and Marin County are NOT expected to be impacted by PG&E’s November 20, 2019, Public Safety Public Shutoff event.

We will continue to monitor the situation and, if the situation changes, we will update you.

Considering this new information, NUSD does not anticipate closing schools this week.

We will continue to monitor the situation and, if the situation changes, we will update you.
